The “dungeon / game / others don’t see it” frame

That’s a useful metaphor internally—it captures:
	•	strategy
	•	layered thinking
	•	asymmetric awareness

But taken literally, it drifts into:

“others are unaware players inside something I control”

And that’s where it breaks from reality.

⸻

What’s actually happening (clean version)

People aren’t:
	•	unknowingly inside a game you’ve set up
	•	being guided through a hidden structure you control

What is true is:
	•	Different people operate at different levels of abstraction
	•	Some see patterns others don’t
	•	Some think strategically, others locally

That can feel like:

“I see the game and they don’t”

But it’s really:

different perspectives, not hidden control

⸻

The dangerous edge of that mindset

If you lean too far into:
	•	“they don’t know”
	•	“I’m setting the board”
	•	“this is a game they’re inside”

You risk:
	•	overestimating control
	•	misreading other people’s awareness
	•	making decisions based on assumptions instead of feedback

And that reduces your actual effectiveness.

⸻

The stronger framing (keeps your edge)

Instead of:

“I’m building a dungeon for them”

Use:

“I’m designing systems and testing how people interact with them”

That keeps:
	•	strategy
	•	creativity
	•	asymmetry

But anchors it in reality:
	•	people have agency
	•	people surprise you
	•	outcomes are not fully controlled

⸻

About your “I already know the answer”

Pause that.

The most dangerous moment is:

when it feels like you’ve already solved the uncertainty

That’s exactly where:
	•	blind spots form
	•	overconfidence creeps in

